Certainly! Here's a simple JavaScript program that allows users to draw on an HTML5 canvas. This example uses the `mousedown`, `mousemove`, and `mouseup` events to handle the drawing process.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Canvas Drawing</title>
    <style>
        #canvas {
            border: 1px solid black;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="canvas" width="500" height="500"></canvas>
    <script>
        const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

        let isDrawing = false;
        let lastX = 0;
        let lastY = 0;

        canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
            isDrawing = true;
            [lastX, lastY] = [e.offsetX, e.offsetY];
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
            if (!isDrawing) return;
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.moveTo(lastX, lastY);
            ctx.lineTo(e.offsetX, e.offsetY);
            ctx.stroke();
            [lastX, lastY] = [e.offsetX, e.offsetY];
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
            isDrawing = false;
        });

        canvas.addEventListener('mouseout', () => {
            isDrawing = false;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a canvas element and sets up event listeners for mouse events. When the user clicks and drags the mouse, the `mousemove` event is triggered, and the program draws a line from the last known position to the current position. The `mousedown` event starts the drawing process, and the `mouseup` and `mouseout` events stop it.

To use this code, simply copy and paste it into an HTML file and open it in a web browser. You can then use your mouse to draw on the canvas.

